Comparater in sort

A lambda in C++ is an anonymous function—a function without a name.
General syntax of a lambda:
[capture](parameters) -> return_type {
    // function body
};
Instead of writing:

bool cmp(int a, int b) {
    return a > b;
}
you can write the function directly where it's needed:

sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int a, int b) {
    return a > b;
});

Capture list([]) = The part inside [] specifies which outside variables the lambda may access.
[=]  =  capture all outside variables by value
[&]  =  capture all outside variables by reference

sort(v.begin(), v.end(), cmp);

sort(order.begin(), order.end(),
     [](auto &a, auto &b) {
         if (a.first == b.first)
             return a.second < b.second;
         return a.first > b.first;
     });

If the vector contains elements of type: pair<int,int>, [](auto &a, auto &b) automatically deduces 
auto &a  → pair<int,int>& 
auto &b  → pair<int,int>&

General rule:
To sort in ascending order, use <
To sort in descending order, use >
